Pictured Above: 2022 Mastermind Cohort

What's the one thing that makes you feel most fulfilled? For me, it is encouraging and guiding artists on their own small business journey. But, it can be hard to really get in nitty gritty quirks of each individual's business during a course or a coaching call. That is why I took a big leap this past year and started my own small group mastermind.

I called it "The Creative Hive Mastermind" and it has honestly been the most exhilarating, stretching, and lifegiving thing I've ever done in my career. I welcomed 20 incredible women into this 12 month program, and together, we've (myself included) been challenged to GROW. To stretch ourselves in enormous ways. To build the business habits that lead to growth. And, it has been the biggest joy this year to watch each person's business story unfold.

This is a mastermind for artists focusing on products, licensing, and the occasional service based business. Products are my sweet spot, and building multiple income streams is essential for building stability.

Now, building a business and growing it is HARD. Perhaps building an art business is even harder. But, I've watched firsthand this group of business owners take huge leaps over the last 12 months.

For 2023, there are just a few spots available for my mastermind. This is an application based program. Applications close on Friday, December 9th. If you are interested (serious applications only) apply using the link in my profile or visit https://www.leverageyourart.com/mastermind

Hey there. It’s Stacie. And I made this pattern. And I am 99% sure that I love it. ❤️

I drew it in Procreate with a pencil brush and assembled it in Adobe Illustrator. When I sat down yesterday to work on it, I found myself in a deep, refreshing state of creative flow! Before I knew it, I had stayed up WAY past my usual bed time so it could finish it.

It was a big relief.

When I’m in a dry spell with making art, it almost feels like I’m holding my breath. I feel like I’ve been holding my breath for months.

Drawing this felt like a big exhale. 

I have been in a rut with my own art. I think I must be on the verge of something new in my life and business, because I’m feeling like my creative voice is shifting/growing/evolving once again. I don’t know what it will look like, but I need/crave/feel the change coming.

As someone who has prided themselves in having clear vision for my life and future (I was the girl with a solid 5 year plan)…. the last year has felt a little foggy.

When I look back over the last 14 years of running Gingiber, I feel like there have been several iterations of my art, my voice, and my style. 

These iterations almost always coincide with personal growth (or, even more often, personal struggles that I’m trying so hard to manage). 

So, universe, let me put it out here for you to see in regards to possible change on the horizon: I want to make more art. I want to feel a rush of creative freedom! I want to feel passionate direction. I want my intuition to speak loudly to me. I want to lead with candor and honesty and vulnerability. I want to embody contentment, yet leave room for surprises and spontaneity. 

That’s not too much to ask for, is it?

And if you read this far, tell me: What should I name this pattern? I’m thankful this drawing came to life quickly. It felt like a puzzle, and I had all the pieces. #gingibermakespatterns

14 years ago, on a day off from managing a coffee shop, I opened my Etsy store, Gingiber.

Trends have come and gone, many of my Etsy colleagues have moved onto other careers, and the technology and social media advances have been a whirlwind to keep up with, but Gingiber is still here, 14 years later.

And, besides leading the best team of 20 (seriously 20!) and getting to work along side my sister, Angie, I still find my greatest peace when I get to turn a bunch of crosshatches and pencil lines into something expressive and brand new. 

Here’s to year 14. And here’s to WHO KNOWS how many more years to come. I could end up still running this business 90 years old and still explaining to people where the name “Gingiber” came from ❤️

Art licensing changed the way I approached my business and my life. (woah, Stacie, don’t be so dramatic! 😂) In all seriousness though, it really did! But what IS art licensing? 

It’s when you “rent” your artwork to companies so they can sell products with your artwork on them. In exchange you get paid a royalty (could be 4-11%, but honestly it varies) every time one of those products sells. Or you might get paid a flat fee instead. 

When I introduced art licensing as part of the Gingiber business model, things took off quickly! It gave us an extra income stream and generated more visibility and brand awareness – all without that much extra effort. 

See, when you license your art you don’t have to reinvent the wheel. In fact, you can use art that you ALREADY have and start pitching it to potential licensing partners. 

This is just one strategy I teach in my signature course, Leverage Your Art, which is opening for enrollment in just a few weeks. 

Getting to help other artist’s learn to make an income from their art and realize their dreams is one of the most fulfilling things I do as an artist and educator. It seriously means the world to me to get to share what I’ve learned while building a successful art business with you. 

Leverage Your Art only opens once a year, and that time is almost here!!! I am giddy with excitement!

Keep an eye out for more on that coming soon. And be sure to follow @leverageyourart where I share more business tips and resources for artists!

Unfortunately, I was not transported back in time into the arms of James Alexander Malcolm Mackenzie Fraser. ‘Tis my greatest sorrow.

At least I named my mini van after Jamie. I take solace in that. 🏴󠁧󠁢󠁳󠁣󠁴󠁿

This summer I went on the trip of a lifetime. Scotland is my favorite place in the entire world. And summer in Scotland? It is perfect! 

I’ve been talking about “this trip” for years.

In 2019, I created a vision board and filled it with family goals, financial goals, home goals, and personal goals. 

And since 2019, I’ve experienced all but 1 item on my personal goals: to go back to Scotland with my family. I got really specific on my vision board, right down to the cottage I would stay in, the streets I would walk down, and even the window seat of the coffee shop I wanted to sit in.

This dream has been propelling me forward for nearly 5 years.

Dreams come true. But not by accident. Directing your actions towards the steps that will bring you closer to your hearts desires helps the dream to be realized.

Ralph Waldo Emerson wrote, “The day is always his, who works in it with serenity and great aims.”

I may not always lead a life of serenity, but I lead a life of dreamful intention. And in 2023, I got to cross off one more item from that 2019 vision board. 

Now I get to sit and dream some more. And I’m exited to set my next few “pie in the sky impossible goals”. Because I know that even though “how” these dreams will occur isn’t clear right now, writing down what I want, and putting those goals where I can see them every day will keep me focused towards choosing carefully the steps that might get me closer to them. 

So often we set goals, then experience setbacks and rejections, and we want to curl up and stop dreaming. 

Don’t give up. Even if the dream doesn’t happen when you hoped it would or even still feels impossible, perhaps the hope of the dream can carry you where your supposed to be. 

As happy as I am to have experienced this trip (there’s a lot I’m reflecting on, and I’m eager to share with anyone who cares to listen what I think I’ve come away with) I want to know: what dream have you been holding onto?

I’m not being dramatic when I say that art licensing has changed my life… 👇

Back when Gingiber was just a scrap of an idea, I was working a job where I frequently worked over 40 hours a week. I had just started my Etsy shop, but it wasn’t making a ton of progress. I was raising my first daughter, but there were weeks and months where I barely had a chance to see her before bedtime.

I remember one week in particular where every time I would come home from work to spend time with my family I’d get called back to work before I even made it home. I didn’t see my daughter at all for an entire week.
I missed out on so much the entire first nine months of her life because I was beholden to someone else’s schedule working to build someone else’s dream…

Little did I know, the tiny Etsy shop that I was building in the margins of my life was going to change the course of my family’s life forever.

Starting Gingiber changed EVERYTHING. Not only did it change my family’s life financially, it also allowed me the freedom and flexibility to spend time with my family and put my energy into the things I cared most about all while getting to do what I loved - making art.

I was finally building MY dream, not someone else’s.

And I want that same level of freedom and creative fulfillment for you. Your priorities might be different than mine, and that’s ok. But think about what it could be costing you to hold back on your creative dreams.

Maybe it’s time with family like it was for me, or maybe it’s location freedom, or financial freedom. Whatever it is for you, find your “why” and let it drive you to take action.

You have the power in you to create the big life you dream of.
It’s time to start building YOUR dream, my friend.

Like me, you probably have big art goals for this year, right? But how do you achieve them when time is scarce and you're managing a lot on your own?
​
The key lies in three words: Vision, Reflection, and Action. Let me share a personal story that embodies these elements.
​
Not so long ago, my biggest goal was to write and illustrate a book. I wanted it to happen so badly! Despite pitching to publishers and trying to find a literary agent, I kept facing rejections. The dream seemed increasingly distant after two years of effort.​
​
​Initially, I was heartbroken and set my book ideas aside. Allowing myself to feel sad was essential, but then I gathered the courage to revisit my dream with a fresh approach. I sat down, reassessed my art business goals, and created a vision board. As a doodler, I visualized all my new year's goals and shared them on Instagram, complete with a carefully selected "phrase for the new year."
​
This approach breathed new life into my work. I was inspired and the art I created that year increased in popularity on social media! In a wonderful twist, a literary agent who had previously rejected me noticed my new direction and reached out for a collaboration. Our partnership flourished, and we successfully sold my book, Give Yourself Margin, to Andrews McMeel, which was published in 2020. This journey taught me the transformative power of revisiting and understanding my goals.
​
​Our growth is about more than just setting goals; it's about understanding them deeply. This is crucial for genuine progress.

Now it’s your turn to reflect and start the year off on the right foot. 

P.S. I also know the challenges of balancing creativity with life’s demands, because I'm a mom with 3 kids, 2 dogs, and a growing art business! That’s why I'm excited about a special project I’ve been working on. It's a realistic, artist-friendly plan, set to be unveiled on January 10th, to help you navigate your goals, schedule, and creativity.
